<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>go to ground • go to the ground</xh5><p> <i>go to ground—</i>1. fall down: Larsson claimed a penalty when he <u>went to ground</u> after a tussle with Amoruso. 2. <i>(also: go to earth)</i> go into hiding; put oneself out of sight: Some key gang leaders had been arrested and the assumption was that the others had “<u>gone to ground</u>.”</p><p><i>go to the ground—</i>1. <i>= go to ground 1: </i>Several of us were hit including me who <u>went to the ground</u> in a pool of blood. 2. be overcome; perish: Each vagabond that arrived bent his neck to the yoke of gain.... The strong survived, the weaker <u>went to the ground</u>.</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> The expression does not fully correlate in meaning with the phrase <b>go on the ground</b>—<i><b>= </b>go to the ground 1: </i>She <u>went on the ground</u> and I picked her up and a couple of fellows came along, saying, “Do you want any help, officer?”</p> </entry>
